1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:This paper proposes a unified and general framework for argumentation based negotiation, in which the role of argumentation is formally analyzed .
1-2:The framework makes it possible to study the outcomes of an argumentation based negotiation .
1-3:It shows what an agreement is, how it is related to the theories of the agents, when it is possible, and how this can be attained by the negotiating agents in this case .
1-4:It defines also the notion of concession, and shows in which situation an agent will make one, as well as how it influences the evolution of the dialogue .
1-5:I.2.3 [Deduction and Theorem Proving]: .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Roughly speaking, negotiation is a process aiming at finding some compromise or consensus between two or several agents about some matters of collective agreement, such as pricing products, allocating resources, or choosing candidates .
2-2:Negotiation models have been proposed for the design of systems able to bargain in an optimal way with other agents for example, buying or selling products in ecommerce .
2-3:Different approaches to automated negotiation have been investigated, including game theoretic approaches (which usually assume complete information and unlimited computation capabilities) [11], heuristic based approaches which try to cope with these limitations [6], and argumentation based approaches [2, 3, 7, 8, 9, 12, 13] which emphasize the importance of exchanging information and explanations between negotiating agents in order to mutually influence their behaviors (e.g .
2-4:an agent may concede a goal having a small priority), and consequently the outcome of the dialogue .
2-5:Indeed, the two first types of settings do not allow for the addition of information or for exchanging opinions about offers .
2-6:Integrating argumentation theory in negotiation provides a good means for supplying additional information and also helps agents to convince each other by adequate arguments during a negotiation dialogue .
2-7:Indeed, an offer supported by a good argument has a better chance to be accepted by an agent, and can also make him reveal his goals or give up some of them .
2-8:The basic idea behind an argumentationbased approach is that by exchanging arguments, the theories of the agents (i.e .
2-9:their mental states) may evolve, and consequently, the status of offers may change .
2-10:For instance, an agent may reject an offer because it is not acceptable for it .
2-11:However, the agent may change its mind if it receives a strong argument in favor of this offer .
2-12:Several proposals have been made in the literature for modeling such an approach .
2-13:However, the work is still preliminary .
2-14:Some researchers have mainly focused on relating argumentation with protocols .
2-15:They have shown how and when arguments in favor of offers can be computed and exchanged .
2-16:Others have emphasized on the decision making problem .
2-17:In [3, 7], the authors argued that selecting an offer to propose at a given step of the dialogue is a decision making problem .
2-18:They have thus proposed an argumentationbased decision model, and have shown how such a model can be related to the dialogue protocol .
2-19:In most existing works, there is no deep formal analysis of the role of argumentation in negotiation dialogues .
2-20:It is not clear how argumentation can influence the outcome of the dialogue .
2-21:Moreover, basic concepts in negotiation such as agreement (i.e .
2-22:optimal solutions, or compromise) and concession are neither defined nor studied .
2-23:This paper aims to propose a unified and general framework for argumentation based negotiation, in which the role of argumentation is formally analyzed, and where the existing systems can be restated .
2-24:In this framework, a negotiation dialogue takes place between two agents on a set O of offers, whose structure is not known .
2-25:The goal of a negotiation is to find among elements of O, an offer that satisfies more or less 967 978 81 904262 7 5 c 2007 IFAAMAS the preferences of both agents .
2-26:Each agent is supposed to have a theory represented in an abstract way .
2-27:A theory consists of a set A of arguments whose structure and origin are not known, a function specifying for each possible offer in O, the arguments of A that support it, a non specified conflict relation among the arguments, and finally a preference relation between the arguments .
2-28:The status of each argument is defined using Dung"s acceptability semantics .
2-29:Consequently, the set of offers is partitioned into four subsets: acceptable, rejected, negotiable and non supported offers .
2-30:We show how an agent"s theory may evolve during a negotiation dialogue .
2-31:We define formally the notions of concession, compromise, and optimal solution .
2-32:Then, we propose a protocol that allows agents i) to exchange offers and arguments, and ii) to make concessions when necessary .
2-33:We show that dialogues generated under such a protocol terminate, and even reach optimal solutions when they exist .
2-34:This paper is organized as follows: Section 2 introduces the logical language that is used in the rest of the paper .
2-35:Section 3 defines the agents as well as their theories .
2-36:In section 4, we study the properties of these agents" theories .
2-37:Section 5 defines formally an argumentation based negotiation, shows how the theories of agents may evolve during a dialogue, and how this evolution may influence the outcome of the dialogue .
2-38:Two kinds of outcomes: optimal solution and compromise are defined, and we show when such outcomes are reached .
2-39:Section 6 illustrates our general framework through some examples .
2-40:Section 7 compares our formalism with existing ones .
2-41:Section 8 concludes and presents some perspectives .
2-42:Due to lack of space, the proofs are not included .
2-43:These last are in a technical report that we will make available online at some later time. .
