3-7:Offers correspond to the different alternatives that can be exchanged during a negotiation dialogue .
3-8:For instance, if the agents try to decide the place of their next meeting, then the set O will contain different towns .
3-9:Different arguments can be built from L .
3-10:The set Args(L) will contain all those arguments .
3-11:By argument, we mean a reason in believing or of doing something .
3-12:In [3], it has been argued that the selection of the best offer to propose at a given step of the dialogue is a decision problem .
3-13:In [4], it has been shown that in an argumentation based approach for decision making, two kinds of arguments are distinguished: arguments supporting choices (or decisions), and arguments supporting beliefs .
3-14:Moreover, it has been acknowledged that the two categories of arguments are formally defined in different ways, and they play different roles .
3-15:Indeed, an argument in favor of a decision, built both on an agent"s beliefs and goals, tries to justify the choice; whereas an argument in favor of a belief, built only from beliefs, tries to destroy the decision arguments, in particular the beliefs part of those decision arguments .
3-16:Consequently, in a negotiation dialogue, those two kinds of arguments are generally exchanged between agents .
3-17:In what follows, the set Args(L) is then divided into two subsets: a subset Argso(L) of arguments supporting offers, and a subset Argsb(L) of arguments supporting beliefs .
3-18:Thus, Args(L) = Argso(L) ∪ Argsb(L) .
3-19:As in [5], in what follows, we consider that the structure of the arguments is not known .
3-20:Since the knowledge bases from which arguments are built may be inconsistent, the arguments may be conflicting too .
3-21:In what follows, those conflicts will be captured by the relation RL, thus RL ⊆ Args(L) × Args(L) .
3-22:Three assumptions are made on this relation: First the arguments supporting different offers are conflicting .
3-23:The idea behind this assumption is that since offers are exclusive, an agent has to choose only one at a given step of the dialogue .
3-24:Note that, the relation RL is not necessarily symmetric between the arguments of Argsb(L) .
3-25:The second hypothesis says that arguments supporting the same offer are also conflicting .
3-26:The idea here is to return the strongest argument among these arguments .
3-27:The third condition does not allow an argument in favor of an offer to attack an argument supporting a belief .
3-28:This avoids wishful thinking .
3-29:Formally: Definition 1 .
3-30:RL ⊆ Args(L) × Args(L) is a conflict relation among arguments such that: • ∀a, a ∈ Argso(L), s.t .
3-31:a = a , a RL a • a ∈ Argso(L) and a ∈ Argsb(L) such that a RL a Note that the relation RL is not symmetric .
3-32:This is due to the fact that arguments of Argsb(L) may be conflicting but not necessarily in a symmetric way .
3-33:In what follows, we assume that the set Args(L) of arguments is finite, and each argument is attacked by a finite number of arguments. .
