7-1:In this section, we define formally a protocol that generates argumentation based negotiation dialogues between two negotiating agents P and C .
7-2:The two agents negotiate about an object whose possible values belong to a set both agents .
7-3:For simplicity reasons, we assume that this set does not change during the dialogue .
7-4:The agents are equipped with theories denoted respectively AP , FP , P , RP , DefP , and AC , FC , C , RC , DefC .
7-5:Note that the two theories may be different in the sense that the agents may have different sets of arguments, and different preference relations .
7-6:Worst yet, they may have different arguments in favor of the same offers .
7-7:Moreover, these theories may evolve during the dialogue .
