9-14:Let us now consider the following example .
9-15:Example 8 (Static theories) .
9-16:Let O = {o1, o2} be the set of all possible offers .
9-17:The theory of agent P is AP , FP , P , RP , DefP such that: AP = {a1, a2}, FP (o1) = {a1}, FP (o2) = {a2}, P = {(a1, a2)}, RP = {(a1, a2), (a2, a1)}, DefP = {a1, a2} .
9-18:The argumentation system AP , DefP of this agent will return a1 as an accepted argument, and a2 as a rejected one .
9-19:Consequently, the offer o1 is acceptable and o2 is rejected .
9-20:The theory of agent C is AC , FC , C , RC , DefC such that: AC = {a1, a2}, FC (o1) = {a1}, FC (o2) = {a2}, C = {(a2, a1)}, RC = {(a1, a2), (a2, a1)}, DefC = {a2, a1} .
9-21:The argumentation system AC , DefC of this agent will return a2 as an accepted argument, and a1 as a rejected one .
9-22:Consequently, the offer o2 is acceptable and o1 is rejected .
9-23:The only possible dialogues that may take place between the two agents are the following: P: m1 = P, θ, o1, 0 C: m2 = C, θ, o2, 1 P: m3 = P, a1, o1, 2 C: m4 = C, a2, o2, 3 The second possible dialogue is the following: P: m1 = P, θ, o1, 0 C: m2 = C, a2, o2, 1 P: m3 = P, a1, o1, 2 C: m4 = C, θ, o2, 3 Both dialogues end with failure .
9-24:Note that in both dialogues, the theories of both agents do not change .
9-25:The reason is that the exchanged arguments are already known to both agents .
9-26:The negotiation fails because the agents have conflicting preferences .
9-27:Let us now consider an example in which argumentation will allow agents to reach an agreement .
9-28:Example 9 (Dynamic theories) .
9-29:Let O = {o1, o2} be the set of all possible offers .
9-30:The theory of agent P is AP , FP , P , RP , DefP such that: AP = {a1, a2}, FP (o1) = {a1}, FP (o2) = {a2}, P = {(a1, a2), (a3, a1)}, RP = {(a1, a2), (a2, a1)}, DefP = {(a1, a2)} .
9-31:The argumentation system AP , DefP of this agent will return a1 as an accepted argument, and a2 as a rejected one .
9-32:Consequently, the offer o1 is acceptable and o2 is rejected .
9-33:The theory of agent C is AC , FC , C , RC , DefC such that: AC = {a1, a2, a3}, FC (o1) = {a1}, FC (o2) = {a2}, C = {(a1, a2), (a3, a1)}, RC = {(a1, a2), (a2, a1), (a3, a1)}, DefC = {(a1, a2), (a3, a1)} .
9-34:The argumentation system AC , DefC of this agent will return a3 and a2 as accepted arguments, and a1 as a rejected one .
9-35:Consequently, the offer o2 is acceptable and o1 is rejected .
9-36:The following dialogue may take place between the two agents: P: m1 = P, θ, o1, 0 C: m2 = C, θ, o2, 1 P: m3 = P, a1, o1, 2 C: m4 = C, a3, θ, 3 C: m5 = P, θ, o2, 4 At step 4 of the dialogue, the agent P receives the argument a3 from P .
9-37:Thus, its theory evolves as follows: AP = {a1, a2, a3}, RP = {(a1, a2), (a2, a1), (a3, a1)}, DefP = {(a1, a2), (a3, a1)} .
9-38:At this step, the argument a1 which was accepted will become rejected, and the argument a2 which was at the beginning of the dialogue rejected will become accepted .
9-39:Thus, the offer o2 will be acceptable for the agent, whereas o1 will become rejected .
9-40:At this step 4, the offer o2 is acceptable for both agents, thus it is an optimal solution .
9-41:The dialogue ends by returning this offer as an outcome. .
10 RELATED WORK :
10-1:Argumentation has been integrated in negotiation dialogues at the early nineties by Sycara [12] .
10-2:In that work, the author has emphasized the advantages of using argumentation in negotiation dialogues, and a specific framework has been introduced .
10-3:In [8], the different types of arguments that are used in a negotiation dialogue, such as threats and rewards, have been discussed .
10-4:Moreover, a particular framework for negotiation have been proposed .
10-5:In [9, 13], different other frameworks have been proposed .
10-6:Even if all these frameworks are based on different logics, and use different definitions of arguments, they all have at their heart an exchange of offers and arguments .
10-7:However, none of those proposals explain when arguments can be used within a negotiation, and how they should be dealt with by the agent that receives them .
10-8:Thus the protocol for handling arguments was missing .
10-9:Another limitation of the above frameworks is the fact that the argumentation frameworks they The Sixth Intl .
10-10:Joint Conf .
10-11:on Autonomous Agents and Multi Agent Systems (AAMAS 07) 973 use are quite poor, since they use a very simple acceptability semantics .
10-12:In [2] a negotiation framework that fills the gap has been suggested .
10-13:A protocol that handles the arguments was proposed .
10-14:However, the notion of concession is not modeled in that framework, and it is not clear what is the status of the outcome of the dialogue .
10-15:Moreover, it is not clear how an agent chooses the offer to propose at a given step of the dialogue .
10-16:In [1, 7], the authors have focused mainly on this decision problem .
10-17:They have proposed an argumentation based decision framework that is used by agents in order to choose the offer to propose or to accept during the dialogue .
10-18:In that work, agents are supposed to have a beliefs base and a goals base .
10-19:Our framework is more general since it does not impose any specific structure for the arguments, the offers, or the beliefs .
10-20:The negotiation protocol is general as well .
10-21:Thus this framework can be instantiated in different ways by creating, in such manner, different specific argumentation based negotiation frameworks, all of them respecting the same properties .
10-22:Our framework is also a unified one because frameworks like the ones presented above can be represented within this framework .
10-23:For example the decision making mechanism proposed in [7] for the evaluation of arguments and therefore of offers, which is based on a priority relation between mutually attacked arguments, can be captured by the relation defeat proposed in our framework .
10-24:This relation takes simultaneously into account the attacking and preference relations that may exist between two arguments. .
11-1:In this paper we have presented a unified and general framework for argumentation based negotiation
11-2:Like any other argumentation based negotiation framework, as it is evoked in (e.g
11-3:[10]), our framework has all the advantages that argumentation based negotiation approaches present when related to the negotiation approaches based either on game theoretic models (see e.g
11-4:[11]) or heuristics ([6])
11-5:This work is a first attempt to formally define the role of argumentation in the negotiation process
11-6:More precisely, for the first time, it formally establishes the link that exists between the status of the arguments and the offers they support, it defines the notion of concession and shows how it influences the evolution of the negotiation, it determines how the theories of agents evolve during the dialogue and performs an analysis of the negotiation outcomes
11-7:It is also the first time where a study of the formal properties of the negotiation theories of the agents as well as of an argumentative negotiation dialogue is presented
11-8:Our future work concerns several points
11-9:A first point is to relax the assumption that the set of possible offers is the same to both agents
11-10:Indeed, it is more natural to assume that agents may have different sets of offers
11-11:During a negotiation dialogue, these sets will evolve
11-12:Arguments in favor of the new offers may be built from the agent theory
11-13:Thus, the set of offers will be part of the agent theory
11-14:Another possible extension of this work would be to allow agents to handle both arguments PRO and CONS offers
11-15:This is more akin to the way human take decisions
11-16:Considering both types of arguments will refine the evaluation of the offers status
11-17:In the proposed model, a preference relation between offers is defined on the basis of the partition of the set of offers
11-18:This preference relation can be refined
11-19:For instance, among the acceptable offers, one may prefer the offer that is supported by the strongest argument
11-20:In [4], different criteria have been proposed for comparing decisions
11-21:Our framework can thus be extended by integrating those criteria
11-22:Another interesting point to investigate is that of considering negotiation dialogues between two agents with different profiles
11-23:By profile, we mean the criterion used by an agent to compare its offers.
